Please note that the approach to use 2 different threads working sequentially with synchronized (blocking) message handover is probably only needed when looking at *some particular high-throughput scenarios*. The work associated with each task for each thread must normally be *balanced* (i.e. take a similar amount of CPU cycles) for this to even be beneficial. Or, that output is written to e.g. cloud storage or something that may intermittently stall.

You&#39;re correct in that you must use a thread-safe queue for handover between threads! The easiest approach is to instantiate and set up the interactions between the 2 threads directly (instead of using ExecutorService).

For a code example, please see below. Here we assume the Java objects representing the messages are called `MyMsg` and that the serialized form is `String`-based in both input and output files:

    public class ProcessorExample {

      private static final MyMsg END = new MyMsg(); // used to signal file read finished

      public void processFile(File inFile, File outFile) {
        BlockingQueue&lt;MyMsg&gt; queue = new ArrayBlockingQueue&lt;&gt;(4096);
        Thread reader = new Thread(() -&gt; read(queue, inFile), &quot;reader&quot;);
        Thread writer = new Thread(() -&gt; write(queue, outFile), &quot;writer&quot;);
        reader.start();
        writer.start();
      }

      private void read(BlockingQueue&lt;MyMsg&gt; queue, File inFile) {
        try (BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(inFile))) {
          String line;
          while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {
            queue.put(deserialize(line)); //surround with try/catch to drop failed messages
          }
          queue.put(END);
        } catch (IOException|InterruptedException e) {
            // TODO: Graceful handling of exceptions at file level
        }
      }

      private void write(BlockingQueue&lt;MyMsg&gt; queue, File outFile) {
        try (BufferedWriter writer = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter(outFile))) {
          MyMsg msg;
          while ((msg = queue.take()) != END) {
            writer.write(serialize(msg)); //surround with try/catch to drop failed messages
          }
        } catch (IOException|InterruptedException e) {
          // TODO: Graceful handling of exceptions at file level
        }
      }

