You can use
```java
replaceAll(&quot;`([^`]*)`|(\\*\\*|[_~])((?:(?!\\2).)*)\\2&quot;, &quot;$1$3&quot;)
```
See the [regex demo][1]. *Details*:

 - &lt;code&gt;\`([^\`]\*)\`&lt;/code&gt; - backtick, then any zero or more non-backtick chars (captured into Group 1) and then a backtick
 - `|` - or
 - `(\*\*|[_~])` - Group 2: `**`, `_` or `~`
 - `((?:(?!\\2).)*)` - Group 3: any char, zero or more occurrences but as many as possible that does not start with the char sequence captured into Group 2
 - `\2` - Group 2 value.

See the [Java demo][2]:
```java
String s = &quot;**bold**  _italic_ ~strike~ `**code**`&quot;;
String regex = &quot;(?s)`([^`]*)`|(\\*\\*|[_~])((?:(?!\\2).)*)\\2&quot;;
System.out.println(s.replaceAll(regex, &quot;$1$3&quot;)); 
// =&gt; bold  italic strike **code**
```
For nested markers, replace all markdowns keeping substrings in backticks and as a post-processing step remove the backticks:
```java
import java.util.*;
import java.util.regex.*;

class Test
{
	public static void main (String[] args) throws java.lang.Exception
	{
		String s = &quot;**bold**  _italic_ ~strike~ `**code**` **_bold and italic_**&quot;;
		String rx = &quot;(`[^`]*`)|(\\*\\*|[_~])((?:(?!\\2).)*)\\2&quot;;
		String prev = &quot;&quot;;
		do {
			prev = s;
			s = s.replaceAll(rx, &quot;$1$3&quot;);
		}
		while (!prev.equals(s));
		s = s.replaceAll(&quot;`([^`]*)`&quot;, &quot;$1&quot;);
		System.out.println(s);
	}
}
```
See the [Java demo][3]. Output:
```
bold  italic strike **code** bold and italic
```


